<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERSONAL HEALTH; BRAIN CAN START MOUTH WATERING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ASSOCIATED PRESS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Think about pizza. Thick, cheesy pizza. Think about the smell of pizza. Is 
your mouth watering yet? 
</P>
<P>
 When your mouth waters, you're creating saliva.Saliva helps you eat. Saliva is 
produced by saliva glands. These glands pump out saliva when food is in your 
mouth. 
</P>
<P>
 But sometimes just seeing, smelling or thinking about a favorite food can put 
those glands into high gear. 
</P>
<P>
 Saliva glands get their orders from your brain, which signals your mouth to 
get ready for a meal. 
</P>
<P>
 Saliva softens food, making it easier to chew and swallow. It also contains a 
chemical that helps break down food, so it can be more easily absorbed by the 
body. 
</P>
<P>
 In between meals, saliva kills mouth germs that cause tooth decay. Your body 
makes about a quart and a half of saliva a day. 
</P>
<P>
 Whew! 
</P>
</TEXT>
