<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAFE BICYCLING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * It makes good sense to wear a helmet while bicycling, as you pointed out 
(editorial, Jan. 15). It is especially important in the Los Angeles area, where 
bicycling is inherently dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
 When in Amsterdam recently, I was surprised to see no helmets at all, in a 
city where bicycles are everywhere. Yet they have a much better safety record 
than we do. How can this be? They have a better record because they have strong 
programs to provide safe pathways in order to prevent bicycle-car crashes, 
rather than focus on what will happen to cyclists when they get hit. 
</P>
<P>
 Without letting up on the campaign to protect cyclists' heads, we need to give 
more attention to making Los Angeles a safe place to ride bikes. It will be 
safe only when we make sure that the bicycle rider is treated as the equal of 
the car driver. 
</P>
<P>
 JOEL WOODHULL 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
