<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: SAINT-OUEN; SEEKING A NEW LINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The French Communist Party, in decline for 20 years, opens its annual congress 
in the suburbs of Paris today, with the top agenda item election of a successor 
to veteran leader Georges Marchais, 73, who is retiring. 
</P>
<P>
 The party has seen its support drop from 25% in the 1972 election, when 
Marchais took over and the Communists were the dominant force on the French 
left, to less than 10% last year. 
</P>
<P>
 Though there is no heir apparent, many in the party hope that a new leader 
will revitalize it by modernizing and softening what has been an ideological 
hard line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012594-0068 </DOCNO>
