ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: WESTMINSTER; YARD WASTE TO BE PICKED UP AT CURB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Midway City Sanitary District will begin curbside pickup of yard waste 
such as grass clippings and tree and brush trimmings under a six-month pilot 
program that will start next Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 General Manager Don Snavely said residents should put their waste in separate 
containers from their household trash to make it easier for work crews. 
</P>
<P>
 He urged residents to use trash bins for the green waste rather than plastic 
bags. The collected waste will be taken to a compost facility, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 At the end of the six-month trial period, the program will be evaluated to 
determine if it will be continued, Snavely said. 
</P>
<P>
 "It will help the district comply with state recycling requirements," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The sanitary district serves about 75,000 households -- about 85% of 
Westminster and the western portion of Garden Grove. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information, call the district office at (714) 893-3553. BERT ELJERA 
</P>
