<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: CAMARILLO; MAN CHARGED WITH THEFT OF COMPUTER FILES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DWAYNE BRAY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Ventura County prosecutor on Monday asked a jury to convict a former 
maintenance supervisor at Camarillo-based Siemens Solar Industries of stealing 
confidential computer files from the company. 
</P>
<P>
 George Stockhausen, 46, is charged with burglary and unlawful access of a 
computer. He faces up to three years in state prison on each count. 
</P>
<P>
 On Feb. 27, a Siemens security guard saw Stockhausen, 46, illegally 
downloading computer files in the company's legal office, Deputy Dist. Atty. 
Donna W. Thonis told the Superior Court jury Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 She played a tape-recorded interview in which Stockhausen admitted to Siemens' 
private investigators that he entered the locked office from a rooftop and 
copied some computer files. 
</P>
<P>
 The burglary of the legal office occurred hours after Siemens filed a lawsuit 
against Atlantic Richfield Co. alleging that Arco had failed to disclose 
problems at its Arco Solar plant before selling it to Siemens in 1989. Siemens 
attorney Dana Chambliss said the burglary may have been intended to get 
information about the suit.  
</P>
<P>
 But Stockhausen, who was fired, said he was just trying to get information on 
another Siemens employee rumored to have failed a drug test, according to the 
tape. 
</P>
<P>
 Chambliss testified that she had warned Stockhausen and other Siemens 
employees against entering the private legal office. 
</P>
<P>
 Prosecutor Thonis told the jury that Stockhausen should be convicted 
regardless of his intent because it is illegal to copy computer files without 
permission. 
</P>
<P>
 Thonis has not implicated Arco in the burglary. Atlantic Richfield officials 
have denied charges in the civil lawsuit but could not be reached Monday for 
comment on the Stockhausen case. 
</P>
<P>
 In a brief, one-minute opening statement, defense attorney Kenneth B. Frank 
said Stockhausen "was operating in the scope of his duty" when he copied the 
files, which Stockhausen said he later discarded on the highway. 
</P>
<P>
 The case is expected to go to the jury in Judge Charles W. Campbell Jr.'s 
courtroom this morning. DWAYNE BRAY 
</P>
</TEXT>
