<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012594-0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 007129 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
January 25, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 5; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
120 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Renters' rights -- Renters whose buildings were destroyed in the recent 
earthquake can get refunds for part of their January rent payments depending on 
their lease agreements, said Ted Kimball, president of the California Apartment 
Assn.The lease should state that a renter is due a refund if the building is 
uninhabitable "through no fault of either party." If it doesn't, a landlord may 
deny a refund claim. The Personal Finance column in Sunday's editions 
incorrectly implied that all renters could get refunds. 
</P>
<P>
 Also, the toll-free number for the apartment association's rental hot line is 
not available in the San Fernando Valley. Valley residents seeking apartment 
information can call (818) 374-3240. 
</P>
</TEXT>
